accelerated around 1800 once education (Bildung) assumed a central role for social ascent among the so-called Bildungsbürgertum (cultural bourgeoisie). Many Jews sought to benefit from the professional and social opportunities that university attendance enabled, but they soon discovered that while the state encouraged education as a means of the "moral improvement" of the Jews, it was unwilling to concede them the right to professional careers. Alienated from their ancestral religion and unwilling or unable to return to trading occupations, academized Jews often found themselves leading precarious existences. Many joined the struggle for emancipation or took up the reform of Judaism. Now available in English translation for the first time, Monika Richarz's classic study addresses the far-reaching transformation of German Jewry under the impact of university education. It traces the secularization of Jewish education, the significance of academic education for social assimilation, and the loss of Jewish solidarity with increasing acculturation and emancipation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJewish studentszGermany. 0aJews in the professionszGermany. 0aJewsxEducationzGermany. 0aProfessionszGermany. 4aGerman History. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 4aModern Literature. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aBildungsbürgertum.  aGerman Jewry.  aGerman Jews.  aassimilation.  acultural bourgeoisie.  aeducation.  aemancipation.  alegal restrictions.  aprofessional careers.  asocial assimilation.  auniversity education.1 aBagchee, Joydeep, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeiner, Shmuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeschnitzer, Adolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1